         <OBJECT_CONTRACT>
            <TITLE>
               <P>Bournemouth Hotel Training School Development on West Cliff, Bournemouth</P>
            </TITLE>
            <REFERENCE_NUMBER>DN105975</REFERENCE_NUMBER>
            <CPV_MAIN>
               <CPV_CODE CODE="45000000"/>
            </CPV_MAIN>
            <TYPE_CONTRACT CTYPE="SERVICES"/>
            <SHORT_DESCR>
               <P>The Council is the freehold owner of adjoining sites; one known as the former Winterbourne Hotel and the Beacon Road Public Car Park (together "the Site").</P>
               <P>The Council wished to promote the development of the Site to construct a hotel with a minimum of 180 bedrooms of which a minimum of 120 must be 4-star quality rooms (with additional rooms being 3-star quality)("the Hotel Training School"). The local planning authority has granted planning permission on these sites for a 200-bedroom training hotel with Planning Reference: 7-2015-4917-N.</P>
               <P>The Council ran a procurement process following the open procedure to appoint a developer and operator (the Tenderer) to deliver the Hotel Training School. This process did not result in suitable tenders (as explained in more detail below). The Council therefore used a negotiated procedure to identify a successful Tenderer from those bidders involved in the original procurement process. The Council now intends to award a contract to that Tenderer.</P>
            </SHORT_DESCR>
            <VAL_TOTAL CURRENCY="GBP">64000000</VAL_TOTAL>
            <NO_LOT_DIVISION/>
            <OBJECT_DESCR ITEM="1">
               <CPV_ADDITIONAL>
                  <CPV_CODE CODE="55000000"/>
               </CPV_ADDITIONAL>
               <CPV_ADDITIONAL>
                  <CPV_CODE CODE="66000000"/>
               </CPV_ADDITIONAL>
               <CPV_ADDITIONAL>
                  <CPV_CODE CODE="70000000"/>
               </CPV_ADDITIONAL>
               <n2016:NUTS CODE="UKK21"/>
               <SHORT_DESCR>
                  <P>The Council proposes to fund the design and construction of the Hotel Training School.</P>
                  <P>Under this arrangement, the Tenderer will be required to enter into a Development Agreement (DA) to manage the design and construction process, including appointment of the design team and the works contractor. It should be noted that the DA is conditional upon the grant of planning permission; securing 10-years rental insurance; and securing a fixed price build contract that will allow the Hotel Training School to be delivered within agreed cost/value limits. It is currently anticipated that the construction of the hotel will be completed in 2021.</P>
                  <P>The Tenderer will be required to enter into a Hotel Management Agreement (HMA) with a leading internationally recognised hotel operator / brand (directly or through a hotel management company).</P>
               </SHORT_DESCR>
               <NO_OPTIONS/>
               <NO_EU_PROGR_RELATED/>
               <INFO_ADD>
                  <P>Following the successful construction of the Hotel, the Tenderer will be granted a 35-year lease on full repairing and insuring terms at a commercial rent and will operate it in accordance with the terms of the HMA. The Tenderer will pay a small premium to the Council in respect of this lease.</P>
               </INFO_ADD>
            </OBJECT_DESCR>
         </OBJECT_CONTRACT>
         <PROCEDURE>
            <DIRECTIVE_2014_24_EU>
               <PT_NEGOTIATED_WITHOUT_PUBLICATION>
                  <D_ACCORDANCE_ARTICLE>
                     <D_PROC_OPEN/>
                  </D_ACCORDANCE_ARTICLE>
                  <D_JUSTIFICATION>
                     <P>The Council commenced a competitive procurement process in February 2016 following the open procedure (see OJEU contract notice 2016/S 023-036933) ("the published process"). It issued an Invitation to Tender that sought submissions from tenderers who were able to develop a Hotel Training School on the Site.</P>
                     <P>The Invitation to Tender sought submissions from bidders who were able to develop a quality hotel; manage the design and construction process; and secure a leading internationally recognised hotel operator to run a quality hotel. The Invitation to Tender specified that the bidders were to secure development finance but allowed for the submission of variant bids.</P>
                     <P>The Council considered all the tenders received in response to the Invitation to Tender and concluded that all tenders received were unsuitable. This conclusion was reached on the basis that all tenders received were either not financially and/or operationally acceptable.</P>
                     <P>In light of this, the Council moved to the negotiated procedure without prior publication to identify a suitable provider (under Regulation 32(2)(a) of the Public Contracts Regulations 2015 (as amended)). The Council therefore invited all the qualified economic operators who submitted a tender in the published process to participate in negotiation.</P>
                     <P>As part of the negotiated procedure under Regulation 32(2)(a), the Council reviewed the financial viability of the project based on the Council funding the construction of the Hotel Training School to a specification appropriate to a quality international hotel brand as opposed to the developer funding the project. The Council therefore sought tender submissions in the negotiated procedure based on a Council-funded construction contract (with a revised lease arrangement to reflect the funding structure).</P>
                  </D_JUSTIFICATION>
               </PT_NEGOTIATED_WITHOUT_PUBLICATION>
            </DIRECTIVE_2014_24_EU>
